ation in creating competition and altering racial employment patterns, and the influence of privatization on public employees' earnings. Nuanced analyses, using best practice econometrics, lead the contributors to conclude that while competition helps equalize treatment of employees, it does not eliminate discrimination.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aDiscrimination in employment. 0aSocial marketing. 4aBusiness and Economics : Economy and Society. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh1 aAgesa, Jacqueline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaldwin, Marjorie L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBelfield, Clive, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFealing, Kaye Husbands, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeywood, John S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeywood, John S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJirjahn, Uwe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMonaco, Kristen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO’Halloran, Patrick L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeoples, James H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeoples, James H., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStephan, Gesine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTalley, Wayne K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWei, Xiangdong, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/